hands_on_practices.solution:
1. Polarization drift velocity:
$$\mathbf v_{pi} \;=\;\frac{m_i}{q_i B_0^2}\frac{d\mathbf E_\perp}{dt}\,. $$

2. For a plane wave $\mathbf E_\perp=\mathbf E_0\cos(\mathbf k\cdot\mathbf r-\omega t)$,
$$\frac{d\mathbf E_\perp}{dt}\approx\frac{\partial\mathbf E_\perp}{\partial t}
=-\omega\,\mathbf E_0\sin(\mathbf k\cdot\mathbf r-\omega t)\,,$$
so the amplitude of $\mathbf v_{pi}$ is
$$v_{pi0}=\frac{m_i\omega}{q_iB_0^2}E_0\,. $$

3. Time-averaged kinetic energy density of ions:
$$\langle W_{K,pi}\rangle
=\frac{1}{2}n_i m_i\langle v_{pi}^2\rangle
=\frac{1}{2}n_i m_i\frac{v_{pi0}^2}{2}
=\frac{n_i m_i}{4}\Bigl(\frac{m_i\omega}{q_iB_0^2}E_0\Bigr)^2. $$

4. Time-averaged electric field energy density:
$$\langle W_E\rangle
=\frac{\varepsilon_0}{2}\langle E^2\rangle
=\frac{\varepsilon_0}{2}\frac{E_0^2}{2}
=\frac{\varepsilon_0E_0^2}{4}\,. $$

5. Form the ratio:
$$\frac{\langle W_{K,pi}\rangle}{\langle W_E\rangle}
=\frac{\frac{n_i m_i}{4}\frac{m_i^2\omega^2}{q_i^2B_0^4}E_0^2}
{\frac{\varepsilon_0E_0^2}{4}}
=\frac{n_i m_i^3\omega^2}{\varepsilon_0q_i^2B_0^4}\,. $$

6. Use $\omega_{pi}^2=\frac{n_iq_i^2}{\varepsilon_0m_i}$ and $\omega_{ci}=\frac{q_iB_0}{m_i}$:
$$\frac{\langle W_{K,pi}\rangle}{\langle W_E\rangle}
=\frac{m_i^3\omega^2}{q_i^2B_0^4}\,\frac{n_i}{\varepsilon_0}
=\frac{m_i^4\omega^2\omega_{pi}^2}{q_i^4B_0^4}
=\frac{\omega^2\omega_{pi}^2}{\omega_{ci}^4}\,. $$
